1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,300
In a moment I'm going to tell you about a certain really nice puzzle involving the shadow of a cube.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:09,400
But before we get to that, I should say that the point of this video is not exactly the puzzle per se,

3
00:00:09,820 --> 00:00:15,240
it's about two distinct problem-solving styles that are reflected in two different ways that we can tackle this problem.

4
00:00:15,780 --> 00:00:22,700
In fact, let's anthropomorphize those two different styles by imagining two students, Alice and Bob, that embody each one of the approaches.

5
00:00:23,500 --> 00:00:26,980
So Bob will be the kind of student who really loves calculation.

6
00:00:26,980 --> 00:00:32,820
As soon as there's a moment when he can dig into the details and get a very concrete view of the concrete situation in front of him,

7
00:00:33,060 --> 00:00:34,340
that's where he's the most pleased.

8
00:00:35,120 --> 00:00:38,900
Alice on the other hand is more inclined to procrastinate the computations,

9
00:00:39,280 --> 00:00:42,220
not because she doesn't know how to do them or doesn't want to per se,

10
00:00:42,560 --> 00:00:47,740
but she prefers to get a nice high-level general overview of the kind of problem she's dealing with,

11
00:00:47,800 --> 00:00:51,360
the general shape that it has before she digs into the computations themselves.

12
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:56,200
She's most pleased if she understands not just the specific question sitting in front of her,

13
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:59,780
but also the broadest possible way that you could generalize it,

14
00:00:59,820 --> 00:01:04,380
and especially if the more general view can lend itself to more swift and elegant computations,

15
00:01:04,440 --> 00:01:06,940
once she does actually sit down to carry them out.

16
00:01:13,020 --> 00:01:19,140
Now the puzzle that both of them are going to be faced with is to find the average area for the shadow of a cube.

17
00:01:19,900 --> 00:01:22,320
So if I have a cube kind of sitting here hovering in space,

18
00:01:22,680 --> 00:01:25,460
there are a few things that influence the area of its shadow.

19
00:01:25,460 --> 00:01:29,260
One obvious one would be the size of the cube, smaller cube, smaller shadow.

20
00:01:29,880 --> 00:01:32,080
But also if it's sitting at different orientations,

21
00:01:32,460 --> 00:01:36,160
those orientations correspond to different particular shadows with different areas.

22
00:01:36,780 --> 00:01:41,040
And when I say find the average here, what I mean is average over all possible orientations

23
00:01:41,040 --> 00:01:43,100
for a particular size of the cube.

24
00:01:44,420 --> 00:01:48,100
The astute among you might point out that it also matters a lot where the light source is.

25
00:01:48,360 --> 00:01:52,660
If the light source were very low, close to the cube itself, then the shadow ends up larger.

26
00:01:52,660 --> 00:01:56,200
And if the light source were kind of positioned laterally off to the side,

27
00:01:56,280 --> 00:01:58,560
this can distort the shadow and give it a very different shape.

28
00:01:59,260 --> 00:02:02,660
Accounting for that light position stands to be highly interesting in its own right,

29
00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:07,320
but the puzzle is hard enough as it is, so at least initially, let's do the easiest thing we can

30
00:02:07,320 --> 00:02:11,380
and say that the light is directly above the cube and really far away,

31
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:15,860
effectively infinitely far, so that all we're considering is a flat projection,

32
00:02:16,140 --> 00:02:19,240
in the sense that if you look at any coordinates, x, y, z, in space,

33
00:02:19,520 --> 00:02:21,700
the flat projection would be x, y, 0.

34
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:27,300
So, just to get our bearings, the easiest situation to think about would be if the cube is straight up,

35
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:29,280
with two of its faces parallel to the ground.

36
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:32,780
In that case, this flat projection shadow is simply a square,

37
00:02:33,380 --> 00:02:37,900
and if we say the side lengths of the cube are s, then the area of that shadow is s².

38
00:02:38,740 --> 00:02:42,460
And by the way, any time that I have a label up on these animations, like the one down here,

39
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:45,460
I'll be assuming that the relevant cube has a side length of 1.

40
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:49,520
Now, another special case among all the orientations that's fun to think about

41
00:02:49,520 --> 00:02:53,040
is if the long diagonal is parallel to the direction of the light.

42
00:02:53,600 --> 00:02:56,120
In that case, the shadow actually looks like a regular hexagon,

43
00:02:56,560 --> 00:02:59,680
and if you use some of the methods that we will develop in a few minutes,

44
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:03,580
you can compute that the area of that shadow is exactly the square root of 3

45
00:03:03,580 --> 00:03:05,820
times the area of one of the square faces.

46
00:03:06,660 --> 00:03:11,200
But of course, more often, the actual shadow will be not so regular as a square or a hexagon.

47
00:03:11,660 --> 00:03:16,240
It's some harder to think about shape, based on some harder to think about orientation for this cube.

48
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:21,720
Earlier, I casually threw out this phrase of averaging over all possible orientations,

49
00:03:22,060 --> 00:03:25,300
but you could rightly ask, what exactly is that supposed to mean?

50
00:03:26,160 --> 00:03:29,440
I think a lot of us have an intuitive feel for what we want it to mean,

51
00:03:29,640 --> 00:03:32,860
at least in the sense of what experiment would you do to verify it.

52
00:03:33,060 --> 00:03:38,200
You might imagine tossing this cube in the air, like a die, freezing it at some arbitrary point,

53
00:03:38,620 --> 00:03:42,440
recording the area of the shadow from that position, and then repeating.

54
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:48,380
If you do this many many times, over and over, you can take the mean of your sample.

55
00:03:49,220 --> 00:03:51,720
The number that we want to get at, the true average here,

56
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,540
should be whatever that experimental mean approaches as you do more and more tosses,

57
00:03:56,580 --> 00:03:57,940
approaching infinitely many.

58
00:04:00,440 --> 00:04:04,240
Even still, the sticklers among you could complain that doesn't really answer the question,

59
00:04:04,660 --> 00:04:07,800
because it leaves open the issue of how we're defining a random toss.

60
00:04:08,300 --> 00:04:10,840
The proper way to answer this, if we want it to be more formal,

61
00:04:10,840 --> 00:04:14,920
would be to first describe the space of all possible orientations,

62
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:17,540
which mathematicians have actually given a fancy name.

63
00:04:17,640 --> 00:04:22,440
They call it SO3, typically defined in terms of a certain family of 3x3 matrices.

64
00:04:23,100 --> 00:04:28,760
And the question we want to answer is, what probability distribution are we putting to this entire space?

65
00:04:29,100 --> 00:04:32,000
It's only when such a probability distribution is well-defined,

66
00:04:32,380 --> 00:04:34,500
that we can answer a question involving an average.

67
00:04:35,800 --> 00:04:37,660
If you are a stickler for that kind of thing,

68
00:04:37,660 --> 00:04:40,820
I want you to hold off on that question until the end of the video.

69
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:44,740
You'll be surprised at how far we can get with the more heuristic, experimental idea

70
00:04:44,740 --> 00:04:48,580
of just repeating a bunch of random tosses without really defining the distribution.

71
00:04:49,280 --> 00:04:51,080
Once we see Alice and Bob's solutions,

72
00:04:51,340 --> 00:04:56,480
it's actually very interesting to ask how exactly each one of them defined this distribution along their way.

73
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:01,400
And remember, this is not meant to be a lesson about cube shadows per se,

74
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:03,280
but a lesson about problem solving,

75
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:07,100
told through the lens of two different mindsets that we might bring to the puzzle.

76
00:05:07,860 --> 00:05:09,560
And as with any lesson on problem solving,

77
00:05:09,960 --> 00:05:12,760
the goal here is not to get to the answer as quickly as we can,

78
00:05:12,780 --> 00:05:15,720
but hopefully for you to feel like you found the answer yourself.

79
00:05:16,020 --> 00:05:18,240
So if ever there's a point when you feel like you might have an idea,

80
00:05:18,640 --> 00:05:20,820
give yourself the freedom to pause and try to think it through.

81
00:05:25,420 --> 00:05:29,620
As a first step, and this is really independent of any particular problem solving style,

82
00:05:29,820 --> 00:05:31,460
just any time you find a hard question,

83
00:05:31,460 --> 00:05:33,620
a good thing that you can do is ask,

84
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:38,540
what's the simplest possible, non-trivial variant of the problem that you can try to solve?

85
00:05:39,560 --> 00:05:41,280
So in our case, what you might say is,

86
00:05:41,480 --> 00:05:44,000
okay, let's forget about averaging over all the orientations.

87
00:05:44,120 --> 00:05:45,420
That's a tricky thing to think about.

88
00:05:45,680 --> 00:05:48,200
And let's even forget about all the different faces of the cube,

89
00:05:48,420 --> 00:05:50,860
because they overlap, and that's also tricky to think about.

90
00:05:51,340 --> 00:05:54,500
Just for one particular face, and one particular orientation,

91
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:56,900
can we compute the area of this shadow?

92
00:05:57,660 --> 00:06:00,280
Once more, if you want to get your bearings with some special cases,

93
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:03,220
the easiest is when that face is parallel to the ground,

94
00:06:03,460 --> 00:06:06,680
in which case the area of the shadow is the same as the area of the face.

95
00:06:07,180 --> 00:06:10,080
And on the other hand, if we were to tilt that face 90 degrees,

96
00:06:10,360 --> 00:06:13,440
then its shadow will be a straight line, and it has an area of zero.

97
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:17,420
So Bob looks at this, and he wants an actual formula for that shadow.

98
00:06:17,900 --> 00:06:22,700
And the way he might think about it is to consider the normal vector perpendicular off of that face.

99
00:06:23,180 --> 00:06:26,920
And what seems relevant is the angle that that normal vector makes with the vertical,

100
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:30,080
with the direction where the light is coming from, which we might call theta.

101
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:35,220
Now, from the two special cases we just looked at, we know that when theta is equal to zero,

102
00:06:35,820 --> 00:06:38,880
the area of that shadow is the same as the area of the shape itself,

103
00:06:39,060 --> 00:06:41,560
which is s squared if the square has side lengths s.

104
00:06:42,200 --> 00:06:45,800
And if theta is equal to 90 degrees, then the area of that shadow is zero.

105
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:49,580
And it's probably not too hard to guess that trigonometry will be somehow relevant,

106
00:06:49,900 --> 00:06:54,620
so anyone comfortable with their trig functions could probably hazard a guess as to what the right formula is.

107
00:06:54,620 --> 00:06:57,120
But Bob is more detail-oriented than that.

108
00:06:57,400 --> 00:07:02,020
He wants to properly prove what that area should be, rather than just making a guess based on the endpoints.

109
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:04,740
And the way you might think about it could be something like this.

110
00:07:04,980 --> 00:07:09,380
If we consider the plane that passes through the vertical as well as our normal vector,

111
00:07:09,800 --> 00:07:15,280
and then we consider all the different slices of our shape that are in that plane, or parallel to that plane,

112
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:19,040
then we can focus our attention on a two-dimensional variant of the problem.

113
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:24,180
If we just look at one of those slices, who has a normal vector, an angle theta away from the vertical,

114
00:07:24,180 --> 00:07:26,780
its shadow might look something like this.

115
00:07:27,460 --> 00:07:31,020
And if we draw a vertical line up to the left here, we have ourselves a right triangle.

116
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:37,520
And from here we can do a little bit of angle chasing, where we follow around what that angle theta implies about the rest of the diagram.

117
00:07:38,580 --> 00:07:42,360
And this means the lower right angle in this triangle is precisely theta.

118
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:49,180
So, when we want to understand the size of this shadow in comparison to the original size of the piece,

119
00:07:49,180 --> 00:07:54,580
we can think about the cosine of that angle, theta, which remembers the adjacent over the hypotenuse.

120
00:07:54,700 --> 00:07:58,180
It's literally the ratio between the size of the shadow and the size of the slice.

121
00:07:58,900 --> 00:08:04,520
So, the factor by which the slice gets squished down in this direction is exactly cosine of theta.

122
00:08:05,140 --> 00:08:10,180
And if we broaden our view to the entire square, all the slices in that direction get scaled by the same factor.

123
00:08:10,380 --> 00:08:15,540
But in the other direction, in the one perpendicular to that slice, there is no stretching or squishing,

124
00:08:15,560 --> 00:08:18,120
because the face is not at all tilted in that direction.

125
00:08:18,120 --> 00:08:25,700
So overall, the two-dimensional shadow of our two-dimensional face should also be scaled down by this factor of a cosine of theta.

126
00:08:26,260 --> 00:08:31,340
It lines up with what you might intuitively guess, given the case where the angle is 0° and the case where it's 90°,

127
00:08:31,700 --> 00:08:33,380
but it's reassuring to see why it's true.

128
00:08:34,960 --> 00:08:40,800
And actually, as stated so far, this is not quite correct. There is a small problem with the formula that we've written.

129
00:08:41,340 --> 00:08:46,240
In the case where theta is bigger than 90°, the cosine would actually come out to be negative.

130
00:08:46,240 --> 00:08:51,400
But of course, we don't want to consider the shadow to have negative area, at least not in a problem like this.

131
00:08:51,860 --> 00:08:58,340
So there's two different ways you could solve this. You could say we only ever want to consider the normal vector that is pointing up, that has a positive z component.

132
00:08:58,840 --> 00:09:04,720
Or, more simply, we could say, just take the absolute value of that cosine, and that gives us a valid formula.

133
00:09:06,980 --> 00:09:10,860
So Bob's happy because he has a precise formula describing the area of the shadow.

134
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:14,060
But Alice starts to think about it a little bit differently.

135
00:09:14,060 --> 00:09:20,520
She says, okay, we've got some shape, and then we apply a rotation that sort of situates it into 3D space in some way,

136
00:09:20,780 --> 00:09:24,660
and then we apply a flat projection that shoves that back into two-dimensional space.

137
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:28,340
And what stands out to her is that both of these are linear transformations.

138
00:09:29,060 --> 00:09:32,420
That means that in principle you could describe each one of them with a matrix,

139
00:09:32,780 --> 00:09:36,200
and that the overall transformation would look like the product of those two matrices.

140
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,760
What Alice knows from one of her favorite subjects, linear algebra,

141
00:09:39,760 --> 00:09:44,620
is that if you take some shape and you consider its area, then you apply some linear transformation,

142
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:50,320
then the area of that output looks like some constant times the original area of the shape.

143
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:54,960
More specifically, we have a name for that constant. It's called the determinant of the transformation.

144
00:09:56,260 --> 00:10:00,660
If you're not so comfortable with linear algebra, we could give a much more intuitive description and say,

145
00:10:00,980 --> 00:10:07,560
if you uniformly stretch the original shape in some direction, the output will also uniformly get stretched in some direction.

146
00:10:07,560 --> 00:10:11,400
So the area of each of them should scale in proportion to each other.

147
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:18,320
Now, in principle, Alice could compute this determinant, but it's not really her style to do that, at least not to do so immediately.

148
00:10:18,880 --> 00:10:24,760
Instead, the thing that she writes down is how this proportionality constant between our original shape and its shadow

149
00:10:24,760 --> 00:10:27,100
does not depend on the original shape.

150
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:32,640
We could be talking about the shadow of this cat outline, or anything else, and the size of it doesn't really matter.

151
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:37,420
The only thing affecting that proportionality constant is what transformation we're applying,

152
00:10:37,740 --> 00:10:43,140
which in this context means we could write it down as some factor that depends on the rotation being applied to the shape.

153
00:10:44,500 --> 00:10:48,220
In the back of our mind, because of Bob's calculation, we know what that factor looks like.

154
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:52,500
You know, it's the absolute value of the cosine of the angle between the normal vector and the vertical.

155
00:10:53,160 --> 00:10:56,820
But Alice right now is just saying, yeah, yeah, yeah, I can think about that eventually when I want to.

156
00:10:57,040 --> 00:11:00,480
But she knows we're about to average over all the different orientations anyway,

157
00:11:00,480 --> 00:11:06,800
though she holds out some hope that any specific formula about a specific orientation might get washed away in that average.

158
00:11:08,220 --> 00:11:11,640
Now it's easy to look at this and say, okay, well, Alice isn't really doing anything then.

159
00:11:11,780 --> 00:11:15,440
Of course the area of the shadow is proportional to the area of the original shape.

160
00:11:15,620 --> 00:11:19,640
They're both two-dimensional quantities. They should both scale like two-dimensional things.

161
00:11:20,200 --> 00:11:25,680
But keep in mind, this would not at all be true if we were dealing with the harder case that has a closer light source.

162
00:11:25,840 --> 00:11:27,980
In that case, the projection is not linear.

163
00:11:27,980 --> 00:11:32,880
For example, if I rotate this cat so that its tail ends up quite close to the light source,

164
00:11:33,260 --> 00:11:38,160
then if I stretch the original shape uniformly in the x-direction, say by a factor of 1.5,

165
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:41,780
it might have a very disproportionate effect on the ultimate shadow

166
00:11:41,780 --> 00:11:46,200
because the tail gets very disproportionately blown up as it gets really close to the light.

167
00:11:46,880 --> 00:11:50,740
Again, Alice is keeping an eye out for what properties of the problem are actually relevant

168
00:11:50,740 --> 00:11:53,440
because that helps her know how much she can generalize things.

169
00:11:53,960 --> 00:11:57,260
Does the fact that we're thinking about a square face and not some other shape matter?

170
00:11:57,260 --> 00:12:01,320
No, not really. Does the fact that the transformation is linear matter?

171
00:12:01,820 --> 00:12:02,840
Yes, absolutely.

172
00:12:06,560 --> 00:12:11,760
Alice can also apply a similar way of thinking about the average shadow for any shape like this.

173
00:12:12,020 --> 00:12:16,000
Say we have some sequence of rotations that we apply to our square face.

174
00:12:16,580 --> 00:12:19,560
And let's call them R1, R2, R3, and so on.

175
00:12:19,720 --> 00:12:25,420
Then the area of the shadow in each one of those cases looks like some factor times the area of the square.

176
00:12:25,420 --> 00:12:27,300
And that factor depends on the rotation.

177
00:12:28,060 --> 00:12:32,920
So if we take an empirical average for that shadow across the sample of rotations we're looking at right now,

178
00:12:33,280 --> 00:12:38,320
the way it looks is to add up all of those shadow areas and then divide by the total number that we have.

179
00:12:38,900 --> 00:12:46,460
Now, because of the linearity, this area of the original square can cleanly factor out of all of that, and it ends up on the left.

180
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:52,200
This isn't the exact average that we're looking for, it's just an empirical mean of a sample of rotations.

181
00:12:52,200 --> 00:12:57,640
But in principle what we're looking for is what this approaches as the size of our sample approaches infinity.

182
00:12:57,980 --> 00:13:03,040
And all the parts that depend on the size of the sample sit cleanly away from the area itself.

183
00:13:03,580 --> 00:13:06,460
So whatever this approaches in the limit, it's just going to be some number.

184
00:13:06,820 --> 00:13:09,540
It might be a royal pain to compute, we're not sure about that yet,

185
00:13:09,740 --> 00:13:15,660
but the thing that Alice notes is that it's independent of the size and the shape of the particular 2D thing that we're looking at.

186
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:18,000
It's a universal proportionality constant.

187
00:13:18,460 --> 00:13:24,940
And her hope is that that universality somehow lends itself to a more elegant way to deduce what it must be.

188
00:13:26,260 --> 00:13:31,720
Now Bob would be eager to compute this constant here and now, and in a few minutes I'll show you how he does it.

189
00:13:32,040 --> 00:13:36,960
But before that I do want to stay in Alice's world for a little bit more, because this is where things start to really get fun.

190
00:13:40,080 --> 00:13:44,780
In her desire to understand the overall structure of the question before diving into the details,

191
00:13:44,780 --> 00:13:51,100
she's curious now about how the area of the shadow of the cube relates to the area of its individual faces.

192
00:13:51,620 --> 00:13:54,760
Now if we can say something about the average area of a particular face,

193
00:13:55,240 --> 00:13:58,400
does that tell us anything about the average area of the cube as a whole?

194
00:13:59,100 --> 00:14:05,380
For example, a simple thing we could say is that that area is definitely less than the sum of the areas across all the faces,

195
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:08,920
because there's a meaningful amount of overlap between those shadows.

196
00:14:09,640 --> 00:14:12,540
But it's not entirely clear how to think about that overlap,

197
00:14:12,540 --> 00:14:18,380
because if we focus our attention just on two particular faces, in some orientations they don't overlap at all.

198
00:14:18,460 --> 00:14:20,960
But in other orientations they do have some overlap,

199
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:25,280
and the specific shape and area of that overlap seems a little bit tricky to think about,

200
00:14:25,620 --> 00:14:29,820
much less how on Earth we would average that across all of the different orientations.

201
00:14:30,660 --> 00:14:35,460
But Alice has about three clever insights through this whole problem, and this is the first one of them.

202
00:14:35,880 --> 00:14:40,300
She says, actually, if we think about the whole cube, not just a pair of faces,

203
00:14:40,300 --> 00:14:48,180
we can conclude that the area of the shadow for a given orientation is exactly one half the sum of the areas of all of the faces.

204
00:14:49,580 --> 00:14:53,460
Intuitively you can maybe guess that half of them are bathed in the light and half of them are not,

205
00:14:53,640 --> 00:14:55,660
but here's the way that she justifies it.

206
00:14:55,820 --> 00:15:01,400
She says for a particular ray of light that would go from the sky and eventually hit a point in the shadow,

207
00:15:02,040 --> 00:15:04,860
that ray passes through the cube at exactly two points.

208
00:15:05,120 --> 00:15:07,600
There's one moment when it enters and one moment when it exits.

209
00:15:07,600 --> 00:15:13,780
So every point in that shadow corresponds to exactly two faces above it.

210
00:15:14,460 --> 00:15:19,220
Well, okay, that's not exactly true if that beam of light happened to go through the edge of one of the squares.

211
00:15:19,600 --> 00:15:22,320
There's a little bit of ambiguity on how many faces it's passing.

212
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:25,340
But those account for zero area inside the shadow,

213
00:15:25,380 --> 00:15:29,040
so we're safe to ignore them if the thing we're trying to do is compute the area.

214
00:15:31,020 --> 00:15:35,040
If Alice is pressed and she needs to justify why exactly this is true,

215
00:15:35,040 --> 00:15:38,080
which is important for understanding how the problem might generalize,

216
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:40,820
she can appeal to the idea of convexity.

217
00:15:41,420 --> 00:15:45,440
Convexity is one of those properties where a lot of us have an intuitive sense for what it should mean,

218
00:15:45,600 --> 00:15:48,580
you know, it's shapes that just bulge out, they never dent inward.

219
00:15:49,140 --> 00:15:53,020
But mathematicians have a pretty clever way of formalizing it that's helpful for actual proofs.

220
00:15:53,680 --> 00:15:58,880
They say that a set is convex if the line that connects any two points inside that set

221
00:15:58,880 --> 00:16:01,660
is entirely contained within the set itself.

222
00:16:01,660 --> 00:16:06,380
So, a square is convex because no matter where you put two points inside that square,

223
00:16:06,820 --> 00:16:09,660
the line connecting them is entirely contained inside the square.

224
00:16:10,280 --> 00:16:12,720
But something like the symbol pi is not convex,

225
00:16:12,840 --> 00:16:18,320
I can easily find two different points so that the line connecting them has to peak outside of the set itself.

226
00:16:18,940 --> 00:16:22,600
None of the letters in the word convex are themselves convex.

227
00:16:22,700 --> 00:16:27,020
You can find two points so that the line connecting them has to pass outside of the set.

228
00:16:27,460 --> 00:16:31,420
It's a really clever way to formalize this idea of a shape that only bulges out.

229
00:16:31,420 --> 00:16:35,540
Because anytime that it dents inward, you can find these counterexample lines.

230
00:16:36,100 --> 00:16:41,000
Or, our cube, because it's convex, between the first point of entry and the last point of exit,

231
00:16:41,380 --> 00:16:45,180
it has to stay entirely inside the cube by definition of convexity.

232
00:16:45,740 --> 00:16:49,000
But if we were dealing with some other non-convex shape, like a donut,

233
00:16:49,460 --> 00:16:53,080
you could find a ray of light that enters, then exits, then enters, then exits again,

234
00:16:53,360 --> 00:16:56,160
so you wouldn't have a clean two-to-one cover from the shadows.

235
00:16:56,600 --> 00:17:00,420
The shadows of all of its different parts, if you were to cover this in a bunch of faces,

236
00:17:00,420 --> 00:17:04,080
would not be precisely two times the area of the shadow itself.

237
00:17:04,760 --> 00:17:08,260
So, that's the first key insight, the face shadows double cover the cube shadow.

238
00:17:08,880 --> 00:17:14,660
And the next one is a little bit more symbolic, so let's start things off by abbreviating our notation a little to make room on the screen.

239
00:17:15,360 --> 00:17:19,680
Instead of writing the area of the shadow of the cube, I'm just going to write s of the cube.

