00:21:42,060 --> 00:21:46,140
unless we dig into the details of what it is that she manages to avoid.

307
00:21:46,860 --> 00:21:49,680
So let's take a moment to turn our attention back into Bob's world,

308
00:21:50,220 --> 00:21:52,200
because while Alice has been doing all of this,

309
00:21:52,620 --> 00:21:54,400
he's been busy doing some computations.

310
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:59,300
In fact, what he's been working on is finding exactly what Alice has yet to figure out,

311
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:03,360
which is how to take the formula that he found for the area of a square's shadow

312
00:22:03,360 --> 00:22:07,400
and taking the natural next step of trying to find the average of that square's shadow

313
00:22:07,400 --> 00:22:09,980
averaged over all possible orientations.

314
00:22:14,620 --> 00:22:18,720
So the way Bob starts, if he's thinking about all the different possible orientations for this square,

315
00:22:18,980 --> 00:22:24,160
is to ask, what are all the different normal vectors that that square can have in all these orientations,

316
00:22:24,480 --> 00:22:27,240
because everything about its shadow comes down to that normal vector.

317
00:22:27,800 --> 00:22:32,320
It's not too hard to see that all those possible normal vectors trace out the surface of a sphere,

318
00:22:32,320 --> 00:22:35,560
if we assume it's a unit normal vector, it's a sphere with radius 1.

319
00:22:36,420 --> 00:22:41,580
And furthermore, Bob figures that each point of this sphere should be just as likely to occur as any other.

320
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,320
Our probabilities should be uniform in that way, there's no reason to prefer one direction over another.

321
00:22:47,120 --> 00:22:53,120
But in the context of continuous probabilities, it's not very helpful to talk about the likelihood of a particular individual point,

322
00:22:53,380 --> 00:22:57,440
because in the uncountable infinity of points on the sphere, that would be zero and unhelpful.

323
00:22:57,440 --> 00:23:03,560
So instead, the more precise way to phrase this uniformity would be to say the probability that our normal vector

324
00:23:03,560 --> 00:23:09,440
lands in any given patch of area on the sphere should be proportional to that area itself.

325
00:23:09,960 --> 00:23:15,120
More specifically, it should equal the area of that little patch divided by the total surface area of the sphere.

326
00:23:15,680 --> 00:23:21,060
If that's true, no matter what patch of area we're considering, that's what we mean by a uniform distribution on the sphere.

327
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:26,260
Now to be clear, points on the sphere are not the same thing as orientations in 3D space,

328
00:23:26,260 --> 00:23:31,700
because even if you know what normal vector this square is going to have, that leaves us with another degree of freedom,

329
00:23:31,900 --> 00:23:34,160
the square could be rotated about that normal vector.

330
00:23:34,960 --> 00:23:39,720
But Bob doesn't actually have to care about that extra degree of freedom, because in all of those cases,

331
00:23:40,120 --> 00:23:46,460
the area of the shadow is the same, it's only dependent on the cosine of the angle between that normal vector and the vertical.

332
00:23:47,180 --> 00:23:53,540
Which is kind of neat, all those shadows are genuinely different shapes, they're not the same, but the area of each of them will be the same.

333
00:23:54,720 --> 00:23:59,500
What this means is that when Bob wants this average shadow area over all possible orientations,

334
00:24:00,100 --> 00:24:06,460
all he really needs to know is the average value of this absolute value of cosine of theta for all different possible normal vectors,

335
00:24:06,700 --> 00:24:08,440
all different possible points on the sphere.

336
00:24:09,120 --> 00:24:11,320
So, how do you compute an average like this?

337
00:24:12,540 --> 00:24:19,580
Well, if we lived in some kind of discrete pixelated world, where there's only a finite number of possible angles theta that that normal vector could have,

338
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:21,440
the average would be pretty straightforward.

339
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:26,580
What you do is find the probability of landing on any particular value of theta,

340
00:24:26,700 --> 00:24:30,560
which will tell us something like how much of the sphere do normal vectors with that angle make up,

341
00:24:31,020 --> 00:24:35,940
and then you multiply it by the thing we want to take the average of, this formula for the area of the shadow.

342
00:24:36,860 --> 00:24:44,020
And then you would add that up over all of the different possible values of theta, ranging from 0 up to 180 degrees, or pi radians.

343
00:24:45,060 --> 00:24:50,380
But of course, in reality, there is a continuum of possible values of theta, this uncountable infinity,

344
00:24:50,380 --> 00:24:55,980
and the probability of landing on any specific particular value of theta will actually be 0.

345
00:24:56,680 --> 00:24:59,880
And so a sum like this unfortunately doesn't really make any sense,

346
00:25:00,440 --> 00:25:04,160
or if it does make sense, adding up infinitely many zeros should just give us a 0.

347
00:25:05,800 --> 00:25:08,880
The short answer for what we do instead is that we compute an integral.

348
00:25:09,660 --> 00:25:15,260
And I'll level with you, the hard part here is I'm not entirely sure what background I should be assuming from those of you watching right now.

349
00:25:15,640 --> 00:25:19,800
Maybe it's the case that you're quite comfortable with calculus and you don't need me to belabor the point here.

