00:25:38,860 --> 00:25:43,040
and calling back to the underlying definition is a good way to sort of check yourself in the process.

355
00:25:43,780 --> 00:25:49,940
If we lived in a time before calculus existed and integrals weren't a thing, and we wanted to approximate an answer to this question,

356
00:25:50,420 --> 00:25:56,520
one way we could go about it is to take a sample of values for theta that ranges from 0 up to 180 degrees.

357
00:25:57,180 --> 00:26:02,040
We might think of them as evenly spaced with some sort of difference between each one, some delta theta.

358
00:26:02,620 --> 00:26:09,240
And it's still the case that it would be unhelpful to ask about the probability of a particular value of theta occurring, even if it's 1 in our sample.

359
00:26:09,660 --> 00:26:12,360
That probability would still be 0 and it would be unhelpful.

360
00:26:12,360 --> 00:26:17,920
But what is helpful to ask is the probability of falling between two different values from our sample,

361
00:26:18,040 --> 00:26:22,020
in this little band of latitude with a width of delta theta.

362
00:26:22,400 --> 00:26:29,560
Based on our assumption that the distribution along this sphere should be uniform, that probability comes down to knowing the area of this band.

363
00:26:30,020 --> 00:26:36,720
More specifically, the chances that a randomly chosen vector lands in that band should be that area divided by the total surface area of the sphere.

364
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:45,280
To figure out that area, let's first think of the radius of that band, which, if the radius of our sphere is 1, is definitely going to be smaller than 1.

365
00:26:45,900 --> 00:26:54,780
And in fact, if we draw the appropriate little right triangle here, you can see that that little radius, let's just say at the top of the band, should be the sine of our angle, the sine of theta.

366
00:26:55,520 --> 00:27:00,020
This means that the circumference of the band should be 2 pi times the sine of that angle,

367
00:27:00,560 --> 00:27:05,520
and then the area of the band should be that circumference times its thickness, that little delta theta.

368
00:27:05,520 --> 00:27:09,080
Or rather, the area of our band is approximately this quantity.

369
00:27:09,540 --> 00:27:16,320
What's important is that for a finer sample of many more values of theta, the accuracy of that approximation would get better and better.

370
00:27:17,540 --> 00:27:22,040
Now remember, the reason we wanted this area is to know the probability of falling into that band,

371
00:27:22,420 --> 00:27:28,080
which is this area divided by the surface area of the sphere, which we know to be 4 pi times its radius squared.

372
00:27:28,660 --> 00:27:32,860
That's a value that you could also compute with an integral similar to the one that we're setting up now,

373
00:27:32,860 --> 00:27:36,080
but for now we can take it as a given, as a standard well-known formula.

374
00:27:36,840 --> 00:27:40,880
And this probability itself is just a stepping stone in the direction of what we actually want,

375
00:27:41,080 --> 00:27:43,320
which is the average area for the shadow of a square.

376
00:27:44,240 --> 00:27:48,580
To get that, we'll multiply this probability times the corresponding shadow area,

377
00:27:48,600 --> 00:27:53,020
which is this absolute value of cosine theta expression we've seen many times up to this point.

378
00:27:53,500 --> 00:27:59,340
And our estimate for this average would now come down to adding up this expression across all of the different bands,

379
00:27:59,340 --> 00:28:01,700
all of the different samples of theta that we've taken.

